Statistical machine learning, Lab 1

The aim of this lab is to learn to use R for data input, exploration and visualization. You can learn more about the tools we are using from the book R for Data Science and for quick reference a good resource is collection of cheat sheets from RStudio website: https://www.rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/

Libraries

It is important to keep in mind that R is a collection of main functionality (base R) and various packages and often it is possible to achieve the same goals by using different commands from different packages. Our main package (actually a collection of different packages which work together) is tidyverse package. It is a good idea to load all required libraries in a separate code block (setup chunk) and packages are loaded with library(library_name) command. If a library is not available, it should be installed by using install.packages("package_name") command.

Getting data into R

Data can be in many formats (text files, spreadsheets, SAS/STATA/SPSS data files and so on) and each format requires a different function which is able to understand it. Fortunately there are libraries of such commands available for most common formats, but we’ll consider only text files (for example .csv files).

We consider only data which is in tabular format.

Reading data from text files

The most universal command in the tidyverse for this purpose is read_delim, which can be used for all files for which fields are delimited by a single character. For successful reading of data we should know how missing data is represented, what is separator of fields and what is decimal separator. If data fail is not extremely large, a good program for determining those features visually is Notepad++ for Windows. An alternative which is also available for Mac and Linux is Sublime Text editor (where you have to select a part of text to see invisible characters).

Some moste useful options of this command are:

  • delim='x' (here x is the symbol for delimiter, ’ for tabulator)

  • skip=n (used for leaving out certain number of rows from the beginning)

  • col_names=FALSE if the file does not include column names

  • na=c('..','NA',...) if missing values are denoted by some text

  • n_max=n (maximal number of lines to read, used for skipping lines at the end of file)

  • locale = locale(decimal_mark = ",") for indicating what is used for decimal separator

Data exploration: visualisation

Before starting to fit models to data it is often a good idea to look at visualisation of some variables in the data set. For visualisation we are using ggplot2 library, which is automatically loaded together with tidyverse library. This library makes it quite easy to make nice plots of the data in data frames or tibbles. The logic of commands is very simple - one starts from indicating data frame and then adding different information (layers) to it by specifying which columns are used and how. The simplest scheme of graphing commands is as follows: ggplot(data_frame)+geom_point(aes(x=col1,y=col2,color=col3)) There are different geom_ commands for various types of plots and in addition to color one can specify other characteristics of graph (like point size, symbol and so on)

  • Exercise 5: Produce a scatterplot (point) graph of columns mpg (y-variable) and weight (x-variable) of data imported from Auto.csv. Add information about cylinders to the plot so that color of each point indicates the number of cylinders of the car. See what happens if cylinders is used as color and when factor(cylinders) is used as color.

Solution Graph when color is indicated by the number of cylinders as numeric variable:

ggplot(Auto1)+geom_point(aes(x=weight,y=mpg, col=cylinders))

Output when color is indicated by using cylinders as a factor variable.

ggplot(Auto1)+geom_point(aes(x=weight,y=mpg, col=factor(cylinders)))

  • Exercise 6: Produce a box plot of mpg (y-variable) and factor(cylinder) of data imported from Auto.csv. Is there anything unexpected on the graph?
ggplot(Auto1)+geom_boxplot(aes(x=factor(cylinders),y=mpg))

It seems to be strange that cars with three cylinders use a lot of fuel compared to cars with 4 cylinders. This can be explained by looking more carefully which cars have three cylinders (sports cars in this data set)

Data manipulations

Often we need to do something with data before starting to fit models - add variables, add summary statistics, join different tables and so on. Again, there are several possibilities to do that, but we are using commands from dplyr package, which is automatically loaded with library(tidyverse) command. The logic of this package is that one starts with a data frame (or tibble) and does in sequence several operations (giving output of previous operation as input to the next one) until a desired result is achieved. The operations (like selecting variables, selecting rows, adding new variables, joining data sets and so on) are joined together with |> (newer command, available starting from R version 4.1) or %>% command and most common operations are

  • select() for selecting columns
  • filter() for selecting rows by certain condition
  • group_by for indicating that next operations are done within some groups
  • mutate() for adding new variables (possibly by doing computations within groups). See also help for across() to see how to apply transformations to many columns with a single mutate command.
  • summarise() for computing summary information by groups
  • left_join() for joining data frames by matching some key columns and keeping all rows from the original table
  • ungroup() for removing grouping information if it was necessary only temporarily

There are many other useful operations.

  • Exercise 8: Form a new data set stock_prices by combining AZN and AMZN datasets by date so that column names have suffixes .AZN and .AMZN, respectively. Add variable new to this dataset, where new="new" if date is later than May 31, 2021 and new="old" otherwise (use if_else command for that). Use this dataset to produce scatterplot of closing prices so that color of points is determined by the variable new.

Solution:

stock_prices=AZN |> left_join(AMZN,by="Date",suffix=c(".AZN",".AMZN")) |> mutate(new=if_else(Date>'2021-05-31',"new","old"))
ggplot(stock_prices)+geom_point(aes(x=Close.AZN,y=Close.AMZN,color=new))

  • Exercise 9: Form a new data set Auto3 by selecting only mpg, cylinders, weight and adding to the data imported from Auto.csv variable inv_weight which is computed by 1/weight and also variable mean_mpg, which is average mpg in class with given number of cylinders. Produce scatterplot of mpg with respect to inv_weight.

Solution:

Auto2=Auto1 |>  select(mpg,cylinders,weight) |>  mutate(inv_weight=1/weight) |>  group_by(cylinders) |>  mutate(mean_mpg=mean(mpg))|> ungroup()
ggplot(Auto2)+geom_point(aes(x=inv_weight,y=mpg,color=factor(cylinders)))

Data preprocessing

Often we need to do data manipulation steps repeatedly - for different sets of training data (in order to see how modelling procedure works with different data) before fitting a model and also for new observations before using our model for predictions. All this is possible by using dplyr data manipulation commands, but a neater and much more universal way it to use the R package recipes for this purpose. This package can be used separately but usually it makes sense to use it together with other related data modelling packages, which can be loaded with library(tidymodels). Let us get some idea how this tool can be used.

A data preprocessing recipe allows one to describe how to expand/modify data set by adding, transforming, imputing or normalizing variables, to prepare the recipe for applying (for example by computing means and standard deviations of variables for normalizing; only training data can be used for that) and to apply the transformation by bake() command.

Let us consider preparation of the Auto1 dataset for predictions by creating a recipe which indicates that mpg is the response variable and all other except name predictor variables, transforms origin to a factor variable and normalizes the weight variable.

  • Exercise 10 Perform the following steps:
    • Prepare realistic datasets: all rows without the last one as data available at model fitting time (Auto1_train) and one new vector of x-variables Auto1_newx from the last row with mpg removed with commands Auto1 |> filter(row_number()!=n()) and Auto1 |> filter(row_number()==n())|>select(-mpg)
    • define a recipe with data Auto1_train and formula mpg~.
    • use step_rm() to remove variable name from data
    • use step_num2factor() with levels “one”, “two”, “three” to change origin to a factor variable
    • use sep_normalize() to standardize the weight variable
    • prepare the recipe for usage by using prep() command with option training=Auto1_train. This step computes the mean and standard deviation of the weightvariable, which is used for normalization.
    • create two preprocessed datasets Auto1_train_preproc and Auto1_newx_preproc by using the recipe with bake() command and appropriate datasets.

Solution:

Auto1_train=Auto1 |> filter(row_number()!=n())
Auto1_newx=Auto1 |>  filter(row_number()==n()) |> select(-mpg)
rec1=recipe(mpg~., data=Auto1_train) |> 
  step_rm(name) |> 
  step_num2factor(origin,levels=c("one", "two" ,"three")) |> 
  step_normalize(weight)
tidy(rec1)
rec1_prepared=prep(rec1,Auto1_train)
tidy(rec1_prepared)
Auto1_train_preproc=bake(rec1_prepared,Auto1_train)
Auto1_train_preproc
Auto1_newx_preproc=bake(rec1_prepared,Auto1_newx)
Auto1_newx_preproc
